which is this x right here.

00:02:34.238 --> 00:02:37.405
So let me clean this off for a second.

00:02:38.752 --> 00:02:39.880
And we'll start at the beginning.

00:02:39.880 --> 00:02:44.134
Let's start with the radius
pointing straight sideways.

00:02:44.134 --> 00:02:48.301
And we know that cosine of
theta equals zero is one.

00:02:49.819 --> 00:02:51.992
So if I drop that down,
if I project that down

00:02:51.992 --> 00:02:53.659
onto the angle zero,

00:02:56.251 --> 00:02:58.480
that's this point right here on the curve.

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:02.530
Now as we roll forward,
we go to a higher angle,

00:03:02.530 --> 00:03:06.447
this projection now moves
to here on the curve.

00:03:09.261 --> 00:03:11.761
When the arrow is straight up,

00:03:12.973 --> 00:03:16.129
we are at this point right here,

00:03:16.129 --> 00:03:18.133
we go back to the axis.

00:03:18.133 --> 00:03:21.966
If we go continue on,
this projects down here.

00:03:28.660 --> 00:03:31.243
We're moving this radius vector

00:03:33.550 --> 00:03:35.909
around in a circle like this.

00:03:35.909 --> 00:03:38.127
And actually this one
will be at the same point

00:03:38.127 --> 00:03:41.060
as before, as the one above, but it'll be

00:03:41.060 --> 00:03:43.621
on this part of the curve here.

00:03:43.621 --> 00:03:46.538
And when we get back to zero again,

00:03:48.390 --> 00:03:51.473
the projection is to this point here.

00:03:52.835 --> 00:03:54.793
So that's a way to
visualize the cosine curve

00:03:54.793 --> 00:03:58.960
getting generated by a vector
rotating around this circle.

00:03:59.858 --> 00:04:01.581
The cosine comes out the bottom

00:04:01.581 --> 00:04:03.826
because it's the projection on the x-axis,

00:04:03.826 --> 00:04:05.895
and when we did the sine,
it was the projection

00:04:05.895 --> 00:04:09.867
on the y-axis, produced the
sine wave when we went this way.

00:04:09.867 --> 00:04:13.528
So I like to visualize this
because this rotating vector

00:04:13.528 --> 00:04:16.308
is a really simple and powerful idea,

00:04:16.308 --> 00:04:18.249
and we can see how it actually generates,

00:04:18.249 --> 00:04:21.323
it's a way to generate
sine and cosine waves.

00:04:21.323 --> 00:04:23.283
And you can see how sort of naturally

00:04:23.283 --> 00:04:24.930
they come out at different phases, right.

00:04:24.930 --> 00:04:28.534
The sine starts at zero and
the cosine starts at one.

00:04:28.534 --> 00:04:31.271
With this way of drawing it,
you could see why that happens.

00:04:31.271 --> 00:04:33.291
So this relationship between circles

00:04:33.291 --> 00:04:35.943
and rotating vectors and sines and cosines

00:04:35.943 --> 00:04:37.321
is a very powerful idea.

00:04:37.321 --> 00:04:39.007
We're really gonna take advantage of this.

